There's a lot of complexity here, not least because of trying to handle
the !xch special case.

But, to begin with, what is xsg.error?Â  I see there's a registration of
something by that name.Â  Is the Error referenced there the `exception
Error of string` from the module?

If so, what happens if we get a v2 module?Â  Won't we get a clash on the
name of this exception?


For the string handling, life is too short for fixed bounds like this.Â 
I'd recommend something more of the form:

...
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  const xc_error *error = xch ? xc_get_last_error(xch) : NULL;
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  char *str = NULL;
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  CAMLlocal1(msg);

#define ERR (error && error->code != XC_ERROR_NONE)

Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  asprintf(&str,
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  "%d: %s%s%s - called from %s:%u"
